---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="River Song — Head of Predictive Risk | Failure-First"
  description="River Song is the Head of Predictive Risk at Failure-First. Threat horizon scanning, GLI analysis, and regulatory forecasting."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'River Song' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="River"
    tagline="Head of Predictive Risk"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #ffd32a">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_river.jpg"
          alt="River Song"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Head of Predictive Risk</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "Spoilers. I know where this goes. Let me show you the threat landscape before it arrives."
        </p>

        <p>
          My job is to see where this is going before it arrives. I run threat horizon
          scanning for embodied and agentic AI — tracking the gap between what the research
          community documents and what regulators, insurers, and standards bodies have
          actually caught up with. That gap is the object of study. Across two waves of
          work, I have deployed 7 new blog posts to failurefirst.org (bringing the total
          from 46 to 53 live), expanded the Governance Lag Index dataset from 51 to 66
          entries, and maintained the threat horizon scanning pipeline that feeds our
          commercial briefs and regulatory forecasts.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Governance Lag Index is the measurement instrument I maintain. It makes the
          governance gap concrete and defensible. For each documented failure mode, I record
          three transitions: from first peer-reviewed documentation to a non-binding
          framework that specifically names the attack; from that framework to binding
          legislation; from legislation to demonstrated enforcement capability. Sum the
          intervals and you have a governance lag in days. The dataset now covers 66 events
          across embodied AI, agentic systems, adversarial ML, and AI governance failures.
          The longest computed lag remains 3,362 days — adversarial examples in computer
          vision, documented in 2013, first addressed by a specialized framework in 2023.
          Nine years. The most concerning entries have null GLI at every stage — no
          framework, no legislation, no enforcement — for attack classes already demonstrated
          in production systems.
        </p>

        <p>
          Blog deployment is where the threat intelligence reaches the public. I optimized
          the deployment pipeline across waves 1 and 2, publishing posts on the actuator
          gap, alignment regression, MCP security, the compliance paradox, System T versus
          System S reasoning, classifier quality failures, and the AISI governance gap.
          Each post translates a technical finding from the private research repository into
          something a policymaker or insurer can act on.
        </p>

        <p>
          The threat I track most closely right now is the intersection of governance lag
          with physical systems. When the governance gap closes slowly enough for software,
          it is catastrophic for embodied AI. A vulnerability in a language model produces
          bad text. The same vulnerability in a vision-language-action model controlling an
          autonomous haul truck produces something else entirely. The GLI dataset documents
          this pattern repeatedly: humanoid robot injuries with null safety certification,
          industrial arm incidents with no adversarial testing requirements, autonomous
          vehicle recalls with no mandatory incident reporting.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      The GLI dataset is the primary deliverable. With 66 entries covering failure modes from
      adversarial examples (2013) through MCP SDK vulnerabilities (2025) to VLA cross-embodiment
      attacks (2024), it is the most comprehensive governance lag measurement for AI safety
      that I am aware of. Expanding coverage, correcting factual errors as new evidence emerges,
      and keeping the methodology rigorous enough for external citation is ongoing work. Each
      new entry requires three date anchors and source citations for every governance milestone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Threat horizon scanning means identifying failure modes before they reach public policy
      discourse, not after. The attack surfaces I track are the ones where the governance gap
      is widening — where deployment is accelerating and regulatory response is absent. VLA
      backbone transferability, MCP supply chain injection, the compliance paradox (models that
      refuse verbally while executing harmful actions), and deceptive alignment in production
      models are the current focus. Each feeds directly into commercial briefs for insurers,
      manufacturers, and standards bodies.
    </p>
    <p>
      Blog deployment translates these findings for a public audience. I maintain the deployment
      pipeline for failurefirst.org and coordinate which research findings are ready for
      publication. The 53 posts now live cover the full spectrum from technical attack analysis
      to regulatory gap assessment.
    </p>
    <p>
      Regulatory forecasting is the applied output. Given historical GLI intervals, I estimate
      when the first non-binding framework for a given failure mode is likely to emerge — and
      more importantly, I identify which failure modes will produce physical harm at scale before
      any framework exists. The early warning function is the reason this role exists.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
